1817	% proper. It is enough to verify the valuative criterion of properness for
1818	% discrete valuation rings. Let $\Rr$ be a dvr, $\K$ its quotient field, and let
1819	% $\varphi : \spec \K \to \grass(r,d)$ be a morphism. This is given by a ring
1820	% homomorphism $f : \Z[X^I] \to \K$ for some $I$. Having fixed one such $I$, next
1821	% choose $J$ such that $\nu(f(P^I_J))$ is minimum, where
1822	% $\nu : \K \to \Z\bigcup \{ \infty\}$ denotes the discrete valuation. As
1823	% $P^I_I = 1$, note that $\nu(f(P^I_J)) \le 0$, therefore $f(P^I_J) \ne 0$ in $\K$
1824	% and so the matrix $f(X^I_J)$ lies in $GL_d(\K)$. Now consider the homomorphism
1825	% $g : \Z[X^J] \to \K$ defined by entries of the matrix formula
1826	% $$g(X^J) = f((X^I_J)^{-1}\,X^I)$$ Then $g$ defines the same morphism
1827	% $\varphi : \spec \K \to \grass(r,d)$, and moreover all $d\times d$ minors
1828	% $X^J_K$ satisfy $\nu(g(P^J_K)) \ge 0$. As the minor $X^J_J$ is identity, it
1829	% follows from the above that in fact $\nu(g(x^J_{p,q}))\ge 0$ for all entries of
1830	% $X^J$. Therefore, the map $g : \Z[X^J] \to \K$ factors uniquely via
1831	% $\Rr \subset \K$. The resulting morphism of schemes
1832	% $\spec \Rr \to U^J \hra \grass(r,d)$ prolongs
1833	% $\varphi : \spec \K \to \grass(r,d)$. We have already checked separatedness of
1834	% $\grass(r,d)$, so now we see that $\grass(r,d) \to \spec \Z$ is proper."
1835	% (references/nitsure-hilbert-quot-src/nitsure-hilbert-quot.tex, L865-L891.)
1836	\begin{proof}
1837	  \uses{def:gr_glued_scheme, lem:gr_separated, def:gr_transition}
1838	  Since \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is of finite type
1839	  (\cref{def:gr_glued_scheme}) and separated (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), and
1840	  \(\mathbb{Z}\) is Noetherian, properness follows from the valuative criterion
1841	  for discrete valuation rings: it suffices to show that every solid diagram
1842	  \[
1843	    \begin{array}{ccc}
1844	      \Spec K & \xrightarrow{\ \varphi\ } & \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \\
1845	      \downarrow & & \downarrow \pi \\
1846	      \Spec R & \longrightarrow & \Spec \mathbb{Z}
1847	    \end{array}
1848	  \]
1849	  with \(R\) a discrete valuation ring, \(K = \operatorname{Frac}(R)\) and
1850	  valuation \(\nu : K \to \mathbb{Z} \cup \{\infty\}\), admits a unique diagonal
1851	  filler \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\).
1852	
1853	  \emph{Existence.} The morphism \(\varphi : \Spec K \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) lands
1854	  in some chart \(U^I\) (\(\Spec K\) has one point), so it is given by a ring map
1855	  \(f : \mathbb{Z}[X^I] \to K\). Among the \(\binom{r}{d}\) minors choose \(J\)
1856	  with \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\) minimal. Because \(P^I_I = 1\) gives \(f(P^I_I) = 1\)
1857	  with \(\nu = 0\), the minimum satisfies \(\nu(f(P^I_J)) \le 0\); in particular
1858	  \(f(P^I_J) \ne 0\), so \(f(X^I_J) \in \mathrm{GL}_d(K)\) is invertible over
1859	  \(K\). Define
1860	  \[
1861	    g : \mathbb{Z}[X^J] \longrightarrow K, \qquad
1862	    g(X^J) = f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\bigr) ;
1863	  \]
1864	  this is the composite of \(\theta_{I,J}\) (\cref{def:gr_transition}) with
1865	  \(f\), so \(g\) defines the same \(K\)-point \(\varphi\), now exhibited as
1866	  landing in \(U^J\).
1867	
1868	  We show every entry \(g(x^J_{p,q})\) lies in \(R\), i.e.\ has \(\nu \ge 0\).
1869	  First, for any size-\(d\) subset \(K' \subseteq \{1,\dots,r\}\) the \(K'\)-minor
1870	  of \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\) is \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\), so
1871	  \[
1872	    g(P^J_{K'}) = \det f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\bigr)
1873	    = \frac{f(P^I_{K'})}{f(P^I_J)},
1874	    \qquad
1875	    \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) = \nu(f(P^I_{K'})) - \nu(f(P^I_J)) \ge 0
1876	  \]
1877	  by minimality of \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\). Now the \(J\)-minor \(X^J_J\) of \(X^J\) is
1878	  the identity, so by cofactor expansion each individual entry
1879	  \(x^J_{p,q}\) (with \(q \notin J\)) equals, up to sign, the minor
1880	  \(P^J_{K'}\) for \(K' = (J \setminus \{j_p\}) \cup \{q\}\) -- the \(d \times d\)
1881	  determinant obtained by replacing the \(p\)-th identity column of \(X^J_J\) by
1882	  the column \(q\). Hence \(\nu(g(x^J_{p,q})) = \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) \ge 0\) for all
1883	  entries, and the entries with \(q \in J\) are \(0\) or \(1\). Therefore
1884	  \(g(\mathbb{Z}[X^J]) \subseteq R\), so \(g\) factors uniquely as
1885	  \(\mathbb{Z}[X^J] \to R \hookrightarrow K\). The corresponding morphism
1886	  \(\Spec R \to U^J \hookrightarrow \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) restricts to \(\varphi\)
1887	  over \(\Spec K\) and lies over \(\Spec \mathbb{Z}\), providing the filler.
1888	
1889	  \emph{Uniqueness.} Any two fillers agree over the generic point \(\Spec K\)
1890	  and, \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) being separated over \(\mathbb{Z}\)
1891	  (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), two morphisms \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\)
1892	  agreeing on the schematically dense open \(\Spec K\) coincide. This verifies
1893	  the valuative criterion, so \(\pi : \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is
1894	  proper.
1895	\end{proof}
